1
00:00:01,240 --> 00:00:03,071
NARRATOR:
Previously on The Big Bang Theory:

2
00:00:03,240 --> 00:00:06,596
I'm going to the Arctic Circle with
Leonard, Wolowitz and Koothrappali.

3
00:00:06,760 --> 00:00:08,591
-For three months?
-Yes.

4
00:00:08,920 --> 00:00:12,037
What did you mean when you said
you were going to miss me?

5
00:00:12,519 --> 00:00:13,668
[SIGHS]

6
00:00:13,840 --> 00:00:16,400
It means I wish you weren't going.

7
00:00:29,799 --> 00:00:31,312
Oh, thank God we're home.

8
00:00:31,480 --> 00:00:35,314
I can't believe we spent three months
in that frozen hell.

9
00:00:35,480 --> 00:00:38,836
It was like a snowy nightmare
from which there was no awakening.

10
00:00:39,400 --> 00:00:41,789
I don't know what Arctic expedition
you were on...

11
00:00:41,959 --> 00:00:43,870
...I thought it was a hoot and a half.

12
00:00:47,280 --> 00:00:48,872
Oh, hi, Mom.

13
00:00:49,199 --> 00:00:52,111
No. I told you I'd call you
when I got home. I'm not home yet.

14
00:00:53,600 --> 00:00:55,830
All right. I'm home.

15
00:00:56,280 --> 00:00:58,794
The Arctic expedition
was a remarkable success.

16
00:00:58,960 --> 00:01:01,520
I'm all but certain there's a Nobel Prize
in my future.

17
00:01:01,679 --> 00:01:04,477
Actually, I shouldn't say that.
I'm entirely certain.

18
00:01:06,240 --> 00:01:10,279
No, Mother, I could not feel your
church group praying for my safety.

19
00:01:10,439 --> 00:01:12,395
The fact I'm home safe
doesn't prove it worked.

20
00:01:12,560 --> 00:01:15,313
That logic is post hoc
ergo propter hoc.

21
00:01:16,399 --> 00:01:19,709
No, I'm not sassing you
in Eskimo talk.

22
00:01:20,759 --> 00:01:23,512
-l'm gonna let Penny know we're back.
-Mother, I have to go.

23
00:01:23,680 --> 00:01:26,035
Yeah, love you. Bye.

24
00:01:26,920 --> 00:01:28,672
Hello, old friend.

25
00:01:31,879 --> 00:01:33,153
[SIGHS]

26
00:01:36,800 --> 00:01:38,597
Daddy's home.

27
00:01:41,119 --> 00:01:42,438
Leonard, you're back.

28
00:01:42,600 --> 00:01:44,716
Yeah, I just stopped by to say--

29
00:01:49,559 --> 00:01:51,390
-Yeah, so hi.
-Hi.

30
00:01:59,479 --> 00:02:02,949
Damn it, I should've gone over
and told her we were back.

31
00:02:07,439 --> 00:02:10,636
Yeah, it was first come, first serve.

32
00:02:35,840 --> 00:02:38,593
I just want you both to know,
when I publish my findings...

33
00:02:38,760 --> 00:02:42,309
-...I won't forget your contributions.
-Great.

34
00:02:42,480 --> 00:02:44,516
I can't mention you
in my Nobel acceptance speech.

35
00:02:44,680 --> 00:02:46,193
When I write my memoirs...

36
00:02:46,359 --> 00:02:50,272
...you can expect a very effusive
footnote and perhaps a signed copy.

37
00:02:51,480 --> 00:02:54,074
-We have to tell him.
-Tell me what?

38
00:02:55,160 --> 00:02:57,799
Damn his Vulcan hearing.

39
00:02:58,240 --> 00:03:00,435
You are planning a party for me,
aren't you?

40
00:03:01,240 --> 00:03:02,958
Okay, Sheldon, sit down.

41
00:03:03,719 --> 00:03:06,313
If there's going to be a theme,
I should let you know...

42
00:03:06,480 --> 00:03:08,675
...I don't care for luau, toga
or under the sea.

43
00:03:10,919 --> 00:03:14,070
Yeah. We'll keep that in mind.
Look, we need to talk to you...

44
00:03:14,240 --> 00:03:16,959
...about something that happened
at the North Pole.

45
00:03:17,120 --> 00:03:19,315
If this is about the night
the heat went out...

46
00:03:19,480 --> 00:03:21,948
...there's nothing
to be embarrassed about.

47
00:03:23,159 --> 00:03:26,469
-lt's not about that.
-We agreed to never speak of it again.

48
00:03:26,640 --> 00:03:28,198
So we slept together naked.

49
00:03:31,120 --> 00:03:34,829
It was only to keep our core
body temperatures from plummeting.

50
00:03:35,239 --> 00:03:38,754
-He's speaking about it.
-For me it was a bonding moment.

51
00:03:43,559 --> 00:03:46,153
Sheldon, you remember
the first few weeks...

52
00:03:46,320 --> 00:03:49,756
...we were looking for magnetic
monopoles and not finding anything...

53
00:03:49,919 --> 00:03:53,036
...and you were acting
like an obnoxious giant dictator?

54
00:03:53,200 --> 00:03:55,156
I thought we were gonna be gentle
with him.

55
00:03:55,320 --> 00:03:58,312
That's why I added the "tator."

56
00:04:01,999 --> 00:04:04,274
And when we finally got
our first positive data...

57
00:04:04,440 --> 00:04:05,668
...you were so happy.

58
00:04:05,840 --> 00:04:10,675
Oh, yes. In the world of emoticons,
l was colon, capital D.

59
00:04:15,959 --> 00:04:18,712
Well, ahem, in actuality,
what your equipment detected...

60
00:04:18,879 --> 00:04:22,554
...wasn't so much evidence
of paradigm-shifting monopoles...

61
00:04:22,720 --> 00:04:27,840
...as it was static from the electric
can opener we were turning on and off.

62
00:04:30,240 --> 00:04:32,708
He just went colon, capital O.

63
00:04:35,440 --> 00:04:37,749
-You tampered with my experiment?
-We had to.

64
00:04:37,919 --> 00:04:41,753
It was the only way to keep you
from being such a huge Dickensian.

65
00:04:42,599 --> 00:04:45,318
You see that? I added the "ensian."

66
00:04:46,400 --> 00:04:48,072
Did Leonard know about this?

67
00:04:48,240 --> 00:04:50,913
Leonard's my best friend.
Surely Leonard didn't know.

68
00:04:51,080 --> 00:04:52,672
-It was his idea.
-Of course it was.

69
00:04:52,840 --> 00:04:54,876
The whole plan reeks of Leonard.

70
00:04:56,319 --> 00:04:58,196
-I missed you so much.
-I missed you too.

71
00:04:58,359 --> 00:05:01,795
-I couldn't think of anyone else.
-Me neither.

72
00:05:02,599 --> 00:05:05,193
Except for one night
when the heat went out.

73
00:05:06,599 --> 00:05:08,908
Long story. It's-- Don't ask.

74
00:05:10,039 --> 00:05:11,028
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

75
00:05:11,199 --> 00:05:13,554
SHELDON:
Leonard. Leonard. Leonard.

76
00:05:14,879 --> 00:05:18,076
[WHISPERS]
Do not make a sound.

77
00:05:18,400 --> 00:05:21,153
SHELDON:
Whispering, "Do not make a sound"...

78
00:05:22,039 --> 00:05:24,075
...is a sound.

79
00:05:25,160 --> 00:05:27,754
Damn his Vulcan hearing.

80
00:05:27,920 --> 00:05:30,434
Not a good time, Sheldon.

81
00:05:30,840 --> 00:05:31,829
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

82
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:33,877
SHELDON:
Penny. Penny. Penny.

83
00:05:34,039 --> 00:05:35,233
Ugh, this is ridiculous.

84
00:05:35,399 --> 00:05:36,798
[LEONARD GROANS]

85
00:05:36,960 --> 00:05:38,518
-What?
-Hello, Penny.

86
00:05:38,679 --> 00:05:41,989
I realize you're currently at the mercy
of your biological urges.

87
00:05:42,160 --> 00:05:46,438
As you have a lifetime of poor decisions
ahead of you, may I interrupt this one?

88
00:05:47,720 --> 00:05:49,278
Great to see you too. Come on in.

89
00:05:50,279 --> 00:05:53,237
Wolowitz has informed me
of your grand deception.

90
00:05:53,399 --> 00:05:55,071
Do you have anything to say?

91
00:05:55,240 --> 00:05:58,596
Yes, I feel terrible about it.
I will never forgive myself.

92
00:05:58,759 --> 00:06:02,195
I don't expect you to. I'd appreciate it
if you'd leave me with Penny...

93
00:06:02,359 --> 00:06:05,510
...for a session of self-criticism
and repentance.

94
00:06:08,799 --> 00:06:10,835
Can someone tell me
what's going on here?

95
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:15,357
What's going on is l was led to believe
I was making strides in science...

96
00:06:15,519 --> 00:06:17,589
...when in fact
I was being fed false data...

97
00:06:17,760 --> 00:06:21,912
...at the hands of Wolowitz, Koothrappali
and your furry little boy toy.

98
00:06:23,320 --> 00:06:24,548
Is that true?

99
00:06:24,719 --> 00:06:28,109
-It was the only way to make him happy.
-Why'd you have to make him happy?

100
00:06:28,280 --> 00:06:30,953
Because when he wasn't happy
we wanted to kill him.

101
00:06:32,480 --> 00:06:34,471
That was even a plan.

102
00:06:35,480 --> 00:06:37,550
We were going to throw
his Kindle outside...

103
00:06:37,720 --> 00:06:41,713
...and when he went to get it, lock
the door and let him freeze to death.

104
00:06:42,040 --> 00:06:44,395
-That seems like a bit of an overreaction.
-No.

105
00:06:44,559 --> 00:06:47,949
The overreaction was to tie your limbs
to four different sled-dog teams...

106
00:06:48,119 --> 00:06:50,075
...and yell, "Mush!"

107
00:06:51,919 --> 00:06:55,753
Look, we kept the original data.
You can still publish the actual results.

108
00:06:55,919 --> 00:06:58,558
Yes, but the actual results
are unsuccessful.

109
00:06:58,720 --> 00:07:01,280
I sent an e-mail
to everyone at the university...

110
00:07:01,440 --> 00:07:03,032
...explaining l confirmed
string theory...

111
00:07:03,200 --> 00:07:05,555
...and forever changed
man's understanding of the universe.

112
00:07:05,720 --> 00:07:08,029
Oh. See, yeah, you probably
shouldn't have done that.

113
00:07:09,559 --> 00:07:12,631
So write another e-mail.
Set the record straight. It's no big deal.

114
00:07:14,519 --> 00:07:17,511
You're right, Leonard.
That's not a big deal.

115
00:07:17,679 --> 00:07:20,193
All you did was lie to me,
destroy my dream...

116
00:07:20,359 --> 00:07:23,795
...and humiliate me
in front of the whole university.

117
00:07:25,080 --> 00:07:27,799
That, FYI, was sarcasm.

118
00:07:29,079 --> 00:07:31,718
I, in fact, believe it is a big deal.

119
00:07:33,639 --> 00:07:36,107
-Oh. That poor thing.
-Yeah, I feel terrible.

120
00:07:36,279 --> 00:07:39,191
Wait.
Aren't you gonna go talk to him?

121
00:07:39,359 --> 00:07:42,317
Well, In He'll be fine.
The guy's a trouper. Come here.

122
00:07:42,480 --> 00:07:46,155
No, no, you're right.
You shouldn't talk to him. I will.

123
00:07:48,119 --> 00:07:50,189
Man, I cannot catch a break.

124
00:07:54,959 --> 00:07:56,233
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

125
00:07:57,399 --> 00:08:01,438
-Hey. Do you wanna talk?
-About what?

126
00:08:01,600 --> 00:08:03,352
Being betrayed by my friends?

127
00:08:03,519 --> 00:08:06,636
Spending three months at the North Pole
for nothing?

128
00:08:07,959 --> 00:08:09,551
And I didn't even get to go
to Comic-Con.

129
00:08:09,719 --> 00:08:10,708
[sesame]

130
00:08:13,240 --> 00:08:14,832
Oh, hon--

131
00:08:21,079 --> 00:08:23,832
[SINGING]
Soft kitty, warm kitty

132
00:08:23,999 --> 00:08:26,388
That's for when I'm sick.
Sad is not sick.

133
00:08:26,559 --> 00:08:28,948
Oh, I'm sorry.
I don't know your sad song.

134
00:08:29,120 --> 00:08:31,839
I don't have a sad song.
I'm not a child.

135
00:08:33,360 --> 00:08:36,716
Well, you know, I do understand
what you're going through.

136
00:08:36,879 --> 00:08:39,347
Really? Did you have
the Nobel Prize in waitressing...

137
00:08:39,519 --> 00:08:41,237
...stolen from you?

138
00:08:41,999 --> 00:08:43,398
Well, no.

139
00:08:43,560 --> 00:08:46,199
But, uh, when l was in high school,
one of my friends heard...

140
00:08:46,360 --> 00:08:49,352
...l was gonna be named
head cheerleader. l was so excited.

141
00:08:49,520 --> 00:08:52,318
My mom even made me
a celebration pie.

142
00:08:52,480 --> 00:08:55,153
Then they named stupid
Valerie Mosbacher head cheerleader.

143
00:08:55,319 --> 00:08:57,355
Big old slutbag.

144
00:08:58,520 --> 00:09:01,796
Are you saying
that you think a celebration pie...

145
00:09:01,959 --> 00:09:05,110
...is even remotely comparable
to a Nobel Prize?

146
00:09:05,280 --> 00:09:08,033
Well, they're pretty tasty.

147
00:09:09,560 --> 00:09:12,358
And on a different
but not unrelated topic...

148
00:09:12,519 --> 00:09:15,158
...based on your current efforts
to buoy my spirits...

149
00:09:15,320 --> 00:09:20,314
...do you truly believe that you
were ever fit to be a cheer leader?

150
00:09:24,680 --> 00:09:27,240
Look, I just don't think
that the guys and Leonard...

151
00:09:27,400 --> 00:09:30,517
...really meant to hurt you.
Theyjust told an unfortunate lie...

152
00:09:30,680 --> 00:09:34,150
...to deal with a difficult situation.
You know what it's like?

153
00:09:34,319 --> 00:09:37,391
Remember the new Star Trek movie?
Kirk has to take over the ship...

154
00:09:37,560 --> 00:09:39,710
...so he tells Spock stuff
he knew wasn't true.

155
00:09:39,879 --> 00:09:42,951
Like saying Spock didn't care
his mom died.

156
00:09:43,439 --> 00:09:46,397
I missed Comic-Con
and the new Star Trek movie?

157
00:09:46,560 --> 00:09:47,834
[sesame]

158
00:09:50,159 --> 00:09:52,912
-I like the new look.
-Thanks.

159
00:09:55,839 --> 00:09:57,511
I call it the Clooney.

160
00:09:58,919 --> 00:10:01,513
I call it the Mario and Luigi,
but whatever.

161
00:10:01,680 --> 00:10:03,113
[LEONARD CHUCKLES]

162
00:10:03,639 --> 00:10:04,958
Hey, how's Sheldon doing?

163
00:10:05,120 --> 00:10:07,714
He came out of his room
wearing his Darth Vader helmet...

164
00:10:07,879 --> 00:10:12,589
...and tried to choke me to death
with the Force, so I'd say a little better.

165
00:10:12,759 --> 00:10:16,547
If I may abruptly change the subject,
did you and Penny finally...? You know.

166
00:10:16,719 --> 00:10:17,868
-Howard.
-I don't care...

167
00:10:18,040 --> 00:10:20,508
...but my genitals wanted me to ask.

168
00:10:20,999 --> 00:10:24,036
Tell your genitals what I do with Penny
is none of their business.

169
00:10:25,319 --> 00:10:27,549
He says they didn't do it.

170
00:10:28,959 --> 00:10:30,677
Sheldon, over here.

171
00:10:39,599 --> 00:10:40,873
[CHOCKING]

172
00:10:44,480 --> 00:10:45,674
What are you doing?

173
00:10:46,680 --> 00:10:48,955
Well, I feel bad for the guy.

174
00:10:51,759 --> 00:10:53,670
Sheldon, why are you sitting
by yourself?

175
00:10:53,840 --> 00:10:55,319
Because I am without friends.

176
00:10:55,480 --> 00:10:58,836
Like the proverbial cheese,
I stand alone.

177
00:10:58,999 --> 00:11:00,637
Even while seated.

178
00:11:00,800 --> 00:11:02,472
Come on. We said we were sorry.

179
00:11:02,639 --> 00:11:04,630
It's going to take more
than an "I'm sorry"...

180
00:11:04,799 --> 00:11:08,712
...and an apology pie from Penny
to make up for what you've done to me.

181
00:11:08,880 --> 00:11:11,235
Hey, Cooper.
Read your retraction e-mail.

182
00:11:11,399 --> 00:11:13,674
Way to destroy your reputation.

183
00:11:14,600 --> 00:11:17,990
You see? People have been pointing
and laughing at me all morning.

184
00:11:18,160 --> 00:11:19,639
It's not true.

185
00:11:19,799 --> 00:11:22,677
People have been pointing and laughing
at you your whole life.

186
00:11:22,839 --> 00:11:25,353
All right, I've had enough.
Attention, everyone.

187
00:11:25,520 --> 00:11:27,112
I'm Dr. Sheldon Cooper.

188
00:11:27,280 --> 00:11:29,475
As many of you
in the Physics Department know...

189
00:11:29,639 --> 00:11:32,107
...my career trajectory
has taken a minor detour.

190
00:11:32,280 --> 00:11:33,918
Off a cliff.

191
00:11:35,600 --> 00:11:38,319
-My credibility may have been damaged.
-Completely wrecked.

192
00:11:38,480 --> 00:11:43,031
But I would like to remind you that in
science there's no such thing as failure.

193
00:11:43,199 --> 00:11:44,712
There once was a man...

194
00:11:44,880 --> 00:11:47,758
...who referred to his prediction
of a cosmological constant...

195
00:11:47,920 --> 00:11:50,070
...as the single biggest blunder
of his career.

196
00:11:50,240 --> 00:11:54,313
That man's name was, surprise, surprise,
Albert Einstein.

197
00:11:56,159 --> 00:11:58,309
Yeah, but research into dark energy
proved...

198
00:11:58,480 --> 00:12:01,472
...Einstein's cosmological constant
was actually right all along.

199
00:12:01,639 --> 00:12:06,076
So you're still, surprise, surprise,
a loser.

200
00:12:08,319 --> 00:12:09,752
Oh, you think you're so clever.

201
00:12:09,920 --> 00:12:13,151
Well, let me just tell you.
While I do not currently have a retort...

202
00:12:13,319 --> 00:12:16,152
...check your e-mail periodically
for a doozy.

203
00:12:20,720 --> 00:12:23,109
So much for our friendship
with Sheldon.

204
00:12:23,280 --> 00:12:26,795
Well, we'll always have the night
the heat went out.

205
00:12:34,999 --> 00:12:35,988
-Hi.
-Hey.

206
00:12:36,160 --> 00:12:39,755
Since we got interrupted last night,
I didn't have a chance to give you this.

207
00:12:40,160 --> 00:12:43,197
Aw, Leonard. You shouldn't have.

208
00:12:44,600 --> 00:12:45,828
Oh, boy. Ha, ha.

209
00:12:47,639 --> 00:12:48,992
What is it?

210
00:12:49,520 --> 00:12:52,239
It's a snowflake from the North Pole.

211
00:12:53,399 --> 00:12:55,435
-Are you serious?
-Uh-huh.

212
00:12:55,600 --> 00:12:56,589
It'll last forever.

213
00:12:56,759 --> 00:13:00,229
l preserved it in a 1-percent solution
of polyvinyl acetal resin.

214
00:13:03,800 --> 00:13:06,712
God, that's the most romantic thing
anyone's ever said to me...

215
00:13:06,879 --> 00:13:09,154
...that I didn't understand.

216
00:13:09,320 --> 00:13:11,151
It's actually a pretty simple process.

217
00:13:11,319 --> 00:13:14,755
You see, cyanoacrylates are monomers,
which polymerize--

218
00:13:18,280 --> 00:13:19,998
Red alert. Leonard, Sheldon ran away.

219
00:13:20,159 --> 00:13:22,673
Man, I cannot catch a break.

220
00:13:23,039 --> 00:13:24,711
So how do you know he ran away?

221
00:13:24,879 --> 00:13:28,667
I mean, he's not answering his phone,
he handed in his resignation...

222
00:13:28,839 --> 00:13:31,751
...and he sent me a text that said,
"I'm running away."

223
00:13:31,919 --> 00:13:33,557
Okay. Thanks for letting me know.

224
00:13:33,719 --> 00:13:35,869
Well-- Leonard.
Aren't you gonna do something?

225
00:13:36,360 --> 00:13:38,794
Well, of course
I'm gonna do something.

226
00:13:38,960 --> 00:13:41,076
Uh, Howard, check the comic-book store.

227
00:13:41,240 --> 00:13:44,915
Raj, go to the Thai restaurant.
I'll stay with Penny in her apartment.

228
00:13:45,080 --> 00:13:46,069
[CELL PHONE RINGS]

229
00:13:46,240 --> 00:13:48,037
Oh, damn it.

230
00:13:48,200 --> 00:13:49,633
It's Sheldon's mother.

231
00:13:49,799 --> 00:13:52,233
A break cannot be caught.

232
00:13:52,400 --> 00:13:53,753
Hi, Mrs. Cooper.

233
00:13:54,560 --> 00:13:55,549
He is?

234
00:13:55,719 --> 00:13:57,949
Sheldon went home to Texas.

235
00:13:58,240 --> 00:14:00,629
Yeah-- No, I know he resigned.

236
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:04,475
Yes, I guess it kind of is our fault.

237
00:14:05,039 --> 00:14:07,599
No, no. You're right.
Someone needs to come talk to him.

238
00:14:07,759 --> 00:14:11,035
Don't worry, I'll take care of it. Yeah.
All right.

239
00:14:12,519 --> 00:14:13,508
New plan.

240
00:14:13,680 --> 00:14:17,468
Howard, you and Raj go to Texas,
I'll stay with Penny in her apartment.

241
00:14:17,920 --> 00:14:20,388
-You're not gonna go with them?
-Well, you know...

242
00:14:20,560 --> 00:14:23,074
...I gave you the snowflake,
and we were kissing, and--

243
00:14:23,240 --> 00:14:25,276
Come on. I don't wanna go to Texas.

244
00:14:26,319 --> 00:14:30,597
Oh, right. And I do? My people already
crossed the desert once. We're done.

245
00:14:33,719 --> 00:14:35,311
Trust me, you'll be fine. See you.

246
00:14:35,800 --> 00:14:38,473
Well, wait a second, Leonard.
Come on. How can you not go?

247
00:14:38,639 --> 00:14:41,028
-He's your best friend.
-But I already saw him naked.

248
00:14:41,199 --> 00:14:42,871
-Just come here.
PENNY: No.

249
00:14:43,079 --> 00:14:45,149
I promise I will be here
when you get back.

250
00:14:45,320 --> 00:14:46,878
Just go help Sheldon.

251
00:14:47,600 --> 00:14:48,794
-Really?
-Yeah.

252
00:14:48,959 --> 00:14:52,190
We waited a few months.
We can wait a few more days.

253
00:14:56,079 --> 00:14:57,751
Maybe you can.

254
00:14:59,639 --> 00:15:01,277
Go.

255
00:15:02,839 --> 00:15:06,354
Boy, you cannot catch a break,
can you?

256
00:15:08,759 --> 00:15:11,114
-Here you go, Shelly.
-Thanks, Mom.

257
00:15:11,280 --> 00:15:13,191
Yeah.

258
00:15:13,879 --> 00:15:17,508
Hold your horses, young man.
Here in Texas, we pray before we eat.

259
00:15:17,680 --> 00:15:18,669
Oh, Mom.

260
00:15:18,839 --> 00:15:22,195
This is not California,
land of the heathen.

261
00:15:23,120 --> 00:15:24,553
Give me.

262
00:15:28,280 --> 00:15:31,317
By his hand we are all--

263
00:15:31,520 --> 00:15:32,509
Fed.

264
00:15:32,680 --> 00:15:35,990
-Give us, Lord, our daily--
-Bread.

265
00:15:36,160 --> 00:15:38,355
-Please know that we are truly--
-Grateful.

266
00:15:38,519 --> 00:15:40,908
-For every cup and every--
-Plateful.

267
00:15:41,079 --> 00:15:42,876
Amen.

268
00:15:44,960 --> 00:15:47,190
Now, that wasn't so hard, was it?

269
00:15:47,720 --> 00:15:51,838
My objection was based
on considerations other than difficulty.

270
00:15:51,999 --> 00:15:54,559
Whatever. Jesus still loves you.

271
00:15:56,839 --> 00:15:59,433
Thank you for carving a smiley face
in my sandwich.

272
00:15:59,600 --> 00:16:02,160
I know how to take care of my baby.

273
00:16:02,319 --> 00:16:06,471
His eyes came out a little thin,
but you can just pretend he's Chinese.

274
00:16:10,160 --> 00:16:12,879
So do you want to talk
about what happened...

275
00:16:13,040 --> 00:16:14,871
...with you and your little friends?

276
00:16:15,400 --> 00:16:17,675
-They're not my friends.
-All right.

277
00:16:18,400 --> 00:16:19,674
[MARY CHUCKLES]

278
00:16:20,239 --> 00:16:24,152
If you recall, when you were little
we sat right here at this very spot...

279
00:16:24,320 --> 00:16:28,029
...and talked about the problems you had
getting along with the neighbor kids.

280
00:16:28,199 --> 00:16:31,077
That was different. They were
threatened by my intelligence...

281
00:16:31,240 --> 00:16:34,118
...and too stupid to know
that's why they hated me.

282
00:16:36,080 --> 00:16:39,117
Oh, baby, they knew very well
why they hated you.

283
00:16:50,079 --> 00:16:52,229
I can't believe
you bought a red cowboy hat.

284
00:16:52,400 --> 00:16:55,790
Hello? I'm wearing a red turtleneck.

285
00:16:59,439 --> 00:17:02,351
Plus it was the only boys' large
they had.

286
00:17:03,800 --> 00:17:06,837
I'm sorry. This does not look like Texas.
Where's the tumbleweeds?

287
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:09,036
-Where's the saloons?
-Saloons?

288
00:17:09,199 --> 00:17:10,951
Like in the movies I saw growing up.

289
00:17:11,120 --> 00:17:13,793
You know, uh, 4 for Texas,
Yellow Rose of Texas.

290
00:17:13,960 --> 00:17:18,351
This neighborhood
is more Texas Chainsaw Massacre.

291
00:17:18,599 --> 00:17:20,669
l was really hoping to see a cattle drive.

292
00:17:20,839 --> 00:17:22,158
What can I tell you?

293
00:17:22,319 --> 00:17:25,789
They probably have steaks on sale
at that big-ass Costco over there.

294
00:17:33,319 --> 00:17:34,308
[DOORBELL RINGS]

295
00:17:34,480 --> 00:17:36,789
Will you please take that stupid hat off?

296
00:17:36,959 --> 00:17:38,392
No, I wanna blend in.

297
00:17:40,120 --> 00:17:42,350
To what? Toy Story?

298
00:17:44,480 --> 00:17:45,913
Hi, boys.

299
00:17:46,080 --> 00:17:49,152
-Howdy, ma'am.
-Howdy to you too. You got here quick.

300
00:17:49,319 --> 00:17:50,877
-We took the redeye.
-Come on in.

301
00:17:51,039 --> 00:17:52,472
Thank you kindly.

302
00:17:52,640 --> 00:17:55,313
-Can I get you something to drink?
-No, thank you.

303
00:17:55,480 --> 00:17:59,598
If y'all don't mind,
I got a hankering for a Lone Star Beer.

304
00:18:00,959 --> 00:18:05,111
There's no alcohol in this household,
stop talking like that and lose the hat.

305
00:18:06,919 --> 00:18:10,116
Sorry. I'll take a diet Yoo-hoo
if you have it.

306
00:18:10,880 --> 00:18:11,869
You'll take a cola.

307
00:18:13,199 --> 00:18:15,235
What about you? Raj, is it?

308
00:18:15,679 --> 00:18:18,398
Oh, you still having trouble talking
to the ladies? Ha-ha-ha.

309
00:18:18,559 --> 00:18:20,151
Because, you know, at our church...

310
00:18:20,320 --> 00:18:22,276
...we have a woman
who's an amazing healer.

311
00:18:22,439 --> 00:18:25,112
Mostly she does crutch
and wheelchair people...

312
00:18:25,279 --> 00:18:27,474
...but I bet she'd be willing
to take a shot...

313
00:18:27,640 --> 00:18:30,791
...at whatever Third-World demon
is running around inside of you.

314
00:18:33,159 --> 00:18:36,196
If you don't mind, there's a 3:05
nonstop back to Los Angeles...

315
00:18:36,359 --> 00:18:38,873
...and you have no idea
how much I wanna be on it.

316
00:18:39,520 --> 00:18:41,750
-A girl?
-Uh, yes, ma'am.

317
00:18:41,919 --> 00:18:44,149
Oh, good. I've been praying for you.

318
00:18:47,120 --> 00:18:49,236
Oh, Sheldon.

319
00:18:49,400 --> 00:18:50,594
What are they doing here?

320
00:18:50,760 --> 00:18:52,193
-We came to apologize.
-Again.

321
00:18:52,360 --> 00:18:55,352
And bring you home.
Pack up your stuff and we'll head back.

322
00:18:56,800 --> 00:18:58,791
No. This is my home now.

323
00:18:58,960 --> 00:19:02,999
Thanks to you, my career is over.
I will spend the rest of my life here...

324
00:19:03,159 --> 00:19:06,276
...trying to teach evolution
to creationists.

325
00:19:08,959 --> 00:19:10,631
You watch your mouth, Shelly.

326
00:19:11,680 --> 00:19:13,432
Everyone's entitled to their opinion.

327
00:19:13,600 --> 00:19:15,989
Evolution isn't an opinion, it's fact.

328
00:19:16,159 --> 00:19:19,435
And that is your opinion.

329
00:19:21,839 --> 00:19:23,192
I forgive you. Let's go home.

330
00:19:27,520 --> 00:19:28,509
[CHUCKLES]

331
00:19:28,680 --> 00:19:31,194
Don't tell me prayer doesn't work.

332
00:19:38,240 --> 00:19:41,391
How about that?
Finally caught a break.

333
00:19:41,559 --> 00:19:42,833
Uh-huh.

334
00:19:42,999 --> 00:19:44,273
[PENNY CHUCKLES]

335
00:19:46,640 --> 00:19:50,599
You know how they say
when friends have sex it can get weird?

336
00:19:50,760 --> 00:19:52,273
Sure.

337
00:19:53,199 --> 00:19:57,272
-Why does it have to get weird?
-Pbbt. I don't know.

338
00:19:57,440 --> 00:20:02,150
I mean, we were friends
and now we're more than friends.

339
00:20:02,319 --> 00:20:07,029
And we're whatever this is.
But why label it, right? I mean--

340
00:20:07,199 --> 00:20:08,427
It is what it is and--

341
00:20:08,600 --> 00:20:09,589
-Leonard?
-Yeah?

342
00:20:09,760 --> 00:20:11,751
-lt's weird.
-Totally.

343
00:20:37,719 --> 00:20:39,710
